red form of the variant <b>Arnodt</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Arnott","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from a place called Arnot in Portmoak, Kinross.","Scottish and English: variant of   Arnold  .","English: variant of   Arnett  ."]},{"name":"Jarnot","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alphonse.","Polish: from the personal name <i>Jarnot</i>, an adaptation of German   Arnot  . It occurs mainly in western part of Greater Poland and on the borderland of Silesia and Lesser Poland (the areas of old German settlement in Poland).","French: variant of   Garneau  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Arnot was born in 1360, in Kinross-shire, Scotland, his father, Sir Henry Arnot, was 30 and his mother, Margaret Oliphant, was 26. He had at least 2 sons with Mary Brown. He died after 1413, in his hometown."},"et":{"1360–after 1413":"1360–pärast 1413","1360–1413":"1360–1413","1374–Male":"1374–Surnud","1376–Male":"1376–Surnud","1360–1405":"1360–1405","1385–1450":"1385–1450","1388–Male":"1388–Surnud","1330–1404":"1330–1404","1335–Female":"1335–Surnud","1385":"1385","1330":"1330","1374":"1374","1450":"1450","1360":"1360","1404":"1404","after 1413":"pärast 1413","1413":"1413","1335":"1335","1388":"